<p>&nbsp;In this post I'm going to go over customizations I've made to WSL to make my life easier. <br /><br />The Windows Subsystem for Linux&nbsp; is as the name implies, a Linux subsystem within Windows. This allows for bash scripting, (personally) easier command line management of files, among other things.&nbsp;<span></span></p><!--more--><p></p><p><br /></p><p>To install wsl you should navigate to the Windows Store and choose your distribution.&nbsp;</p><p>While your in the store install Windows Terminal as well have a better 
client for both powershell and your new wsl. Follow the instructions to 
complete the base installation.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Go ahead and upgrade to wsl2 with this guide. <br />https://www.omgubuntu.co.uk/how-to-install-wsl2-on-windows-10<br /> </p><p><br /></p><p><img alt="" src="data:image/png;base64," />&nbsp;</p><p>First things first make sure to update all your packages. I personally use Debian so I'm going to use apt as the example here. Opensuse and Alpine Linux both use separate package managers. This should apply to Ubuntu as well. <br /><br />"apt update"<br />"apt upgrade"</p><p>If you are not the root user (which you are not by default) you will have to prepend the apt commands with "sudo" to "do" this action as a super user (root). <br /></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p>----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br />Here are some packages I use daily along with a small description of each. To make your life easier.<br />You can install these on Debian based installations (Ubuntu included) using sudo apt install &lt;package-name&gt;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>tmux - tmux is a terminal multiplexer that allows for you to split the screen into separate instances so to speak. Check out the souce code here&nbsp;</p><p>https://github.com/tmux/tmux <br /></p><p>&nbsp;otherwise install (on debian based OS) with apt install<br /></p><p></p><p><img alt="" src="data:image/png;base64," /></p><p>&nbsp;^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^</p><p>Spaceship - For my terminal prompt. It's a little complex to install for laymen but I like the way it looks. Check it out: https://github.com/spaceship-prompt/spaceship-prompt</p><p>Neovim - As my go to text editor, if you like vim you'll love neovim. An "upgraded" version of vim with extended support for plugins. If you like tinkering with configs this is for you. <br />Read more about it here: https://neovim.io/</p><p><br /></p><p>For most other situations if I need reccomendations on Linux software, whether for a virtual machine or wsl in this instance. I consult <br />https://github.com/luong-komorebi/Awesome-Linux-Software</p><p>which has an enormous list of software for most occasions. <br /><br />Thanks for reading!!!!<br /><br /><br /></p><p><br /></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;<br /></p>
